Okay, I'm unmuted, but for some reason I can't start my video, which is fine, but you can all hear me?

29
00:02:40,157 --> 00:02:40,817
Yes.

30
00:02:41,517 --> 00:02:49,759
Kevin, can we let people... I'm fine being off camera.

31
00:02:50,259 --> 00:02:57,461
Yeah, I don't know why a camera would be...

32
00:02:58,835 --> 00:02:59,776
I can start.

33
00:02:59,796 --> 00:03:04,100
You can let me know if the video starts to work.

34
00:03:05,562 --> 00:03:15,832
What I'm going to do first is read some prepared remarks so that I remember to cover everything that I want to share with you, and then open it up to questions, because I'm sure you will have questions.

35
00:03:15,852 --> 00:03:17,213
Oh, I've got to start my video.

36
00:03:18,194 --> 00:03:18,675
Allow.

37
00:03:19,295 --> 00:03:20,777
I think we're going to... Here we are.

38
00:03:21,655 --> 00:03:22,956
Let me re-angle that, okay.

39
00:03:24,017 --> 00:03:28,499
Tobacco is still the leading cause of preventable death in the US.

40
00:03:28,939 --> 00:03:34,482
Every year, almost 500,000 Americans die prematurely of smoking-related disease.

41
00:03:35,103 --> 00:03:38,104
Billions of dollars are spent on smoking-related illness.

42
00:03:39,305 --> 00:03:41,026
And so what have we done about this?

43
00:03:42,226 --> 00:03:44,408
It's not new, we've known about it for a long time.

44
00:03:44,808 --> 00:03:46,028
What exactly have we done?

45
00:03:46,129 --> 00:03:48,150
Well, the feds have done some things.

46
00:03:49,881 --> 00:03:58,445
In 2009, the federal government banned flavored cigarettes, although their legislation exempted menthol, so we still had menthol-flavored cigarettes.

47
00:03:59,485 --> 00:04:03,327
The feds also have significant restrictions on tobacco advertising.

48
00:04:04,067 --> 00:04:18,273
And the FDA recently banned menthol cigarettes and flavored cigars on a national basis, a national level, but unfortunately, the White House has delayed signing the law, I'm sure for political reasons.

49
00:04:19,730 --> 00:04:23,791
Meanwhile, local boards of health have done a lot.

50
00:04:23,851 --> 00:04:32,692
Local boards led the campaign for smoke-free workplace law two decades ago against extreme pushback, especially from restaurants and bars.

51
00:04:33,853 --> 00:04:38,373
But the boards had the conviction and the courage to adopt this very progressive regulation.

52
00:04:38,834 --> 00:04:46,475
And now we can't imagine going into a restaurant, theater, or bar, or riding on a bus, train, or subway where someone is smoking.

53
00:04:47,402 --> 00:04:52,467
Local boards have adopted many tobacco control regulations to help reduce youth access to tobacco.

54
00:04:53,048 --> 00:04:57,012
Local boards like this one were early adopters of T21, pharmacy ban,

55
00:04:58,722 --> 00:05:04,064
flavor restriction, cigar minimum price, permit cap, and proximity bans.

56
00:05:04,965 --> 00:05:07,606
Some of these regulations have made their way into state law.

57
00:05:08,066 --> 00:05:21,832
In fact, the usual way that public health regulations get passed is that local boards adopt first, then when there's a critical mass of municipalities that have that regulation, a state law is passed, and eventually federal law.

58
00:05:23,180 --> 00:05:27,601
So what has happened with all this legislation, regulation, and policy change?

59
00:05:27,761 --> 00:05:28,902
What has it accomplished?

60
00:05:29,662 --> 00:05:31,382
It's moved the needle a bit.

61
00:05:31,982 --> 00:05:33,603
However, people still smoke.

62
00:05:34,343 --> 00:05:37,564
Millions are still affected by smoking and secondhand smoke.

63
00:05:38,144 --> 00:05:40,905
And vaping is still a serious issue in our schools.

64
00:05:42,276 --> 00:05:49,742
The tobacco industry is literally cooking up new and clever ways to attract new users.

65
00:05:50,543 --> 00:05:56,748
10 years ago, it was the pink and purple foil-wrapped little cigars or cigarillos for 69 and 79 cents.

66
00:05:57,368 --> 00:06:08,257
And I know all of you are aware of the damage caused by Juul e-cigarettes, the cool, sleek design that came in appealing flavors like mango, fruit medley, and creme brulee.

67
00:06:09,038 --> 00:06:15,740
They look like flash drives, making it hard for parents and school personnel to recognize when seeing one on a desk or in a book bag.

68
00:06:17,301 --> 00:06:19,202
Now we have nicotine pouches.

69
00:06:19,562 --> 00:06:26,004
And by the way, Marianne does have some photos of these products, which she can share either now or later.

70
00:06:26,844 --> 00:06:29,946
But you will be able to see the products that I'm talking about.

71
00:06:31,546 --> 00:06:36,808
Nicotine pouches are made with nicotine salts, and they have a very high nicotine content.

72
00:06:38,014 --> 00:06:42,177
They're even more discreet than vapes, and they're very, very cheap.

73
00:06:42,818 --> 00:06:52,406
A tin of 15 little pouches contains more nicotine, or I'm sorry, I should say, contains the nicotine equivalent of two and a half packs of Marlboros.

74
00:06:53,127 --> 00:07:01,193
And while two and a half packs of Marlboros cost about $32 in Massachusetts, a tin of Zin costs as little as $3.49.

75
00:07:03,701 --> 00:07:13,014
These products are so new, although spreading widely and being used widely, the state DOR, Department of Revenue, doesn't even have an excise tax on them.

76
00:07:15,176 --> 00:07:17,460
Can you see the screen?

77
00:07:17,740 --> 00:07:19,102
Oh, and there's a display of ZIN.

78
00:07:19,142 --> 00:07:19,963
Thank you, Mary Ann.

79
00:07:20,545 --> 00:07:24,866
So there's a display with a sign indicating $3.49 a tin if you buy two.

80
00:07:25,266 --> 00:07:29,387
And then those are the little tins that the Zyn pouches come in.

81
00:07:29,427 --> 00:07:32,627
And they're typically, they're 15 pouches to a tin.

82
00:07:33,007 --> 00:07:37,308
There are other brands, but this is the most common in this area.

83
00:07:38,808 --> 00:07:49,170
We've heard that some young people start their gym workout by popping a Zyn pouch or even two pouches into their mouth before lifting weights because of the big hit or buzz that they get.

84
00:07:50,175 --> 00:07:56,978
This makes addiction even more likely, and I'm now seeing more and more store shelf space taken up by these products.

85
00:07:58,119 --> 00:08:02,141
As I mentioned earlier, Massachusetts banned flavored products almost four years ago.

86
00:08:02,961 --> 00:08:12,186
Earlier this year, we started seeing Newport non-menthol, and there's a photo in the packet for this also, cigarettes.

87
00:08:12,246 --> 00:08:15,948
It's the same green packaging, which we've been told

88
00:08:16,655 --> 00:08:19,416
can trigger an ex-menthol smoker to pick up again.

89
00:08:19,436 --> 00:08:32,162
It turns out that while these so-called non-menthol cigarettes do not contain traditional menthol flavoring, they do contain a chemical that tricks your brain into thinking that what you just inhaled is menthol.

90
00:08:33,023 --> 00:08:36,184
Menthol, you may be aware, is more addicting and harder to quit.

91
00:08:37,925 --> 00:08:43,988
The sign just above the display of packages of tobacco, that sign, which is a little small in this photo,

92
00:08:44,865 --> 00:08:48,307
says non-menthol for the menthol smoker.

93
00:08:48,868 --> 00:08:50,028
They're not even subtle.

94
00:08:51,529 --> 00:08:54,831
One of the latest products I've heard about is the highlighter vape.

95
00:08:55,572 --> 00:08:57,153
And again, there's a photo in the packet.

96
00:08:58,093 --> 00:09:04,477
Taking a page out of Jewel's playbook, this vape design is pretty hard for a parent or a teacher to spot.

97
00:09:05,258 --> 00:09:08,480
I'm guessing these were not designed with you or me in mind.

98
00:09:08,640 --> 00:09:11,021
You'll see what I mean when that photo comes up.

99
00:09:11,662 --> 00:09:13,503
That's actually a vape pen.

100
00:09:15,343 --> 00:09:15,943
What's next?

101
00:09:17,324 --> 00:09:18,104
Nicotine gummies?

102
00:09:18,805 --> 00:09:23,847
There are actually nicotine gummies on the market, just not in Massachusetts because of our flavor ban.

103
00:09:24,928 --> 00:09:29,470
This industry has billions and spends billions on research and development.

104
00:09:30,410 --> 00:09:32,451
We will never catch up or keep up.

105
00:09:33,012 --> 00:09:34,432
They're always one step ahead.

106
00:09:35,573 --> 00:09:41,776
Now may be the time for a strategy that will start us on the path of actually ending nicotine addiction.

107
00:09:43,004 --> 00:09:52,348
In 2020, the town of Brookline passed a bylaw that made it illegal for Brookline retailers to sell tobacco to anyone born after 1-1-2000.

108
00:09:53,549 --> 00:09:54,950
It's a pretty simple policy.

109
00:09:56,010 --> 00:10:03,494
As of 1-1-2020, anyone purchasing a tobacco product has to be born before 1-1-2000.

110
00:10:04,874 --> 00:10:12,238
Brookline retailers have to remember just one date, whereas now the minimum legal sales age changes every single day.

111
00:10:13,261 --> 00:10:18,463
No one who is already 21 loses his or her privilege to purchase and consume tobacco products.

112
00:10:19,164 --> 00:10:23,525
Those not yet 21 will never be able to legally purchase tobacco in Brooklyn.

113
00:10:24,766 --> 00:10:33,730
This policy slowly starts to move us towards the end of nicotine addiction, which again has harmed millions and cost billions for decades.

114
00:10:34,390 --> 00:10:41,173
There's no reason to allow this public health crisis to continue just so the tobacco industry can continue to grow their profits.

115
00:10:42,083 --> 00:10:47,286
In summary, retailers have a long time to get used to no tobacco or lower tobacco sales.

116
00:10:47,986 --> 00:10:54,910
Each year, just one year's worth of potential new buyers will not be able to legally buy tobacco products.

117
00:10:55,470 --> 00:10:56,571
So lots of lead time.

118
00:10:57,091 --> 00:10:58,652
No one has a privilege taken away.

119
00:10:59,192 --> 00:11:00,473
It's easy to administer.

120
00:11:00,493 --> 00:11:05,215
And finally, we move towards a truly nicotine-free generation.

121
00:11:06,936 --> 00:11:10,798
Now what I'd like to do is hear any questions that you might have.

122
00:11:14,770 --> 00:11:17,791
So it's not just tobacco products, it's all nicotine products.

123
00:11:17,891 --> 00:11:18,592
All nicotine.

124
00:11:18,672 --> 00:11:23,053
So including these vape pens that you see, including the nicotine pouches, that's correct.

125
00:11:23,734 --> 00:11:26,915
So where does Brookline's regulations stand right now?

126
00:11:26,935 --> 00:11:28,376
I know they were challenged, right?

127
00:11:29,216 --> 00:11:29,876
Exactly.

128
00:11:29,996 --> 00:11:35,198
So Brookline passed the regulation, or they actually passed it as a town law, a town bylaw.

129
00:11:35,659 --> 00:11:36,859
They are enforcing it.

130
00:11:36,939 --> 00:11:43,862
One of my colleagues has Brookline in her collaborative and she is enforcing and she has issued fines for sales to

131
00:11:44,493 --> 00:11:49,476
someone who was 21, but who became 21 after the birth date restriction.

132
00:11:50,877 --> 00:11:58,281
But meanwhile, six Brookline stores banded together with the support of the tobacco industry, sued Brookline.

133
00:11:58,882 --> 00:12:04,385
That lawsuit was dismissed in district court, Superior Court rather.

134
00:12:04,865 --> 00:12:07,287
And then the industry appealed it.

135
00:12:07,447 --> 00:12:13,431
So it went to the appellate court, but the SJC, the Supreme Judicial Court of Massachusetts,

136
00:12:14,131 --> 00:12:38,112
um sometimes looks down to the appellate court to see what cases are there and if they think there's a case with um broad reach or impact they will move or that it might come to them anyway they'll move that case up to their court which they did in this case so this case is not this lawsuit's not being heard in the appellate court it's being heard by or being decided by the supreme judicial court

137
00:12:38,552 --> 00:12:45,438
There were oral arguments on November 6th, and the justices are now reviewing all the arguments that they heard.

138
00:12:45,879 --> 00:12:51,124
And we hope for a decision, I'm guessing maybe, maybe next month, maybe in January.

139
00:12:52,265 --> 00:12:54,827
And then it's that's the top court in Massachusetts.

140
00:12:54,907 --> 00:12:55,688
Then it becomes law.

141
00:12:57,151 --> 00:13:09,134
And the Attorney General, by the way, already, when Brookline passed this as a bylaw, a bylaw has to be reviewed by the Attorney General's office, and the Attorney General's office already approved the bylaw.

142
00:13:15,916 --> 00:13:17,476
Kevin, can you unmute Kathy?

143
00:13:18,556 --> 00:13:19,917
Okay, I'm unmuted.

144
00:13:20,077 --> 00:13:20,737
That's great.

145
00:13:21,057 --> 00:13:21,477
Thank you.

146
00:13:22,357 --> 00:13:24,018
So I was just going to say, great presentation.

147
00:13:25,552 --> 00:13:28,813
I just, to add one thing, Maureen, I'll never forget this.

148
00:13:29,273 --> 00:13:34,474
I was an ICU nurse, and this was 35 years ago, at least.

149
00:13:34,655 --> 00:13:39,916
I was taking a patient over to test in the bathroom.

150
00:13:40,256 --> 00:13:43,157
I brought the patient into the bathroom, and it said, if you smoke,

151
00:13:44,652 --> 00:13:48,616
which was a menthol, we can't help you.

152
00:13:48,937 --> 00:13:49,978
And I'll never forget that.

153
00:13:50,138 --> 00:13:52,700
So that was 35 years ago.

154
00:13:53,161 --> 00:14:02,309
So, I mean, and being a nursing now over at Mass Eye and Ear seeing all these patients young with asthma and having lots of troubles from the vaping.

155
00:14:02,330 --> 00:14:03,991
So really great work.

156
00:14:04,071 --> 00:14:04,412
Thank you.

157
00:14:05,981 --> 00:14:08,162
Thank you for sharing that, Kathy.

158
00:14:08,323 --> 00:14:09,103
That's pretty moving.

159
00:14:09,183 --> 00:14:11,965
Personal testimonies like that are so moving.

160
00:14:12,005 --> 00:14:13,086
We have all the data.

161
00:14:13,926 --> 00:14:15,988
We have all these reports.

162
00:14:16,048 --> 00:14:18,049
But when you hear things like that, it's very moving.

163
00:14:18,689 --> 00:14:19,310
It really was.

164
00:14:19,330 --> 00:14:20,931
And that was 35 years ago.

165
00:14:21,051 --> 00:14:21,411
Yeah.

166
00:14:22,052 --> 00:14:22,792
Crazy.

167
00:14:23,072 --> 00:14:26,254
And I smoked coals then, so that really resonated with me.

168
00:14:26,775 --> 00:14:27,175
Oh, wow.

169
00:14:27,215 --> 00:14:28,676
Yeah.

170
00:14:29,837 --> 00:14:34,219
And it was having the menthol was the addiction, for sure.

171
00:14:36,632 --> 00:14:38,413
That's what we hear, it's so hard.

172
00:14:39,713 --> 00:14:42,714
Is the goal for Medford to move to that one date as well?

173
00:14:42,734 --> 00:14:44,295
You might have said it and I dismissed it.

174
00:14:46,155 --> 00:14:58,200
So that's kind of the point of the presentation, just so that you have an idea as to what the regulation is about and why, and then we can continue this discussion next month if that's okay.

175
00:14:59,783 --> 00:15:04,085
And then we can move forward, and especially looking and see what happens with Brookline.

176
00:15:04,145 --> 00:15:10,109
I know Mellows and Wakefield are also moving forward with this initiative as well.

177
00:15:10,769 --> 00:15:13,811
So this was just kind of wanted to put it out there.

178
00:15:13,951 --> 00:15:17,173
And then like for Dr. Platt, it was also to be at the next meeting.

179
00:15:17,193 --> 00:15:19,734
Hopefully we can continue the discussion.

180
00:15:19,754 --> 00:15:21,595
Awesome.

181
00:15:22,075 --> 00:15:26,698
Yeah, definitely a great presentation, great materials, and looking forward to hearing more.

182
00:15:28,789 --> 00:15:34,154
If I could, I'd like to update you on what's happened in the, I represent seven communities.

183
00:15:34,214 --> 00:15:38,239
So it's Malden, Medford, Melrose, Wakefield, Winchester, Stoneham and Reading.

184
00:15:38,839 --> 00:15:43,204
So tomorrow, I'll make a similar presentation to the Malden Board of Health.

185
00:15:44,045 --> 00:15:48,370
And then by tomorrow, all seven communities will have heard this presentation.

186
00:15:48,975 --> 00:15:52,800
In addition, three communities have already had a public hearing.

187
00:15:52,820 --> 00:15:56,365
So the next step would be a public hearing.

188
00:15:56,385 --> 00:15:57,827
You don't have to do a public hearing.

189
00:15:57,867 --> 00:16:01,532
A board doesn't have to do a public hearing to adopt a new tobacco regulation.

190
00:16:01,972 --> 00:16:03,574
But because in the past for

191
00:16:05,037 --> 00:16:19,259
When Medford Board of Health passed T21 and a flavor restriction and other tobacco regulations, you did hold a public hearing, then that's kind of expected and it would be wise probably to hold a public hearing.

192
00:16:19,846 --> 00:16:48,972
And at that public hearing, the board would listen to input from both sides or all sides if there are other sides, and they wouldn't respond in any way, but they'd hear that input, the tobacco industry would show up, and maybe some distributors and maybe some retailers, and they'd say why we shouldn't do this, but there would also undoubtedly be some tobacco control folks, advocates for reducing tobacco access, tobacco consumption, tobacco-related disease and death.

193
00:16:49,452 --> 00:17:12,233
So the board would listen to that input, and then maybe the following month, assuming that by then we've heard the SJC decision, and assuming that the SJC voted in favor of the Brookline bylaw, then you would be ready, all the communities would be ready to launch.

194
00:17:12,293 --> 00:17:13,814
So kind of how I see this happening.

195
00:17:14,114 --> 00:17:15,936
Three communities have done public hearings,

196
00:17:16,537 --> 00:17:20,079
I'm hoping that other boards would also vote to do public hearings.

197
00:17:20,539 --> 00:17:21,780
You have the public hearing.

198
00:17:22,120 --> 00:17:23,841
The public hearing is out of the way.

199
00:17:23,921 --> 00:17:25,682
The dust kind of settles on everything.

200
00:17:26,022 --> 00:17:28,384
I'm going to interrupt for one minute.

201
00:17:28,404 --> 00:17:30,285
We have less than a minute in the meeting.

202
00:17:30,345 --> 00:17:31,906
So we're going to end it.

203
00:17:32,066 --> 00:17:37,189
And we decided if people want to rejoin and continue the conversation, that would be awesome.

204
00:17:41,511 --> 00:17:42,572
So everybody, log back in.

205
00:17:44,482 --> 00:17:46,463
So if, you know, if you went forward with it.

206
00:18:03,034 --> 00:18:04,175
Recording in progress.

207
00:18:17,330 --> 00:18:19,131
Okay, sorry about that.

208
00:18:19,271 --> 00:18:21,532
Are we ready?

209
00:18:21,552 --> 00:18:23,313
I believe so.

210
00:18:24,834 --> 00:18:37,020
So anyway, if you if you decided to hold a public hearing sooner rather than later, then when the SJC made their decision, assuming that it's in favor of the of this policy, then you would be ready to launch.

211
00:18:38,914 --> 00:18:45,797
And what our goal would be is to have, if we can work this out, is to have all seven of our communities.

212
00:18:46,297 --> 00:18:54,159
And that's one of the reasons that Anthony Choi is on the call because he's the health director in Melrose, Wakefield and Stoneham.

213
00:18:54,800 --> 00:19:04,023
And it would be great to have this be a regional, each board would decide individually, but it would be great to have the launch date be the same in all seven communities.

214
00:19:04,603 --> 00:19:06,304
So we do a lot of education.

215
